posts.name: Jim Forbes
posts.cooked:
good questionâ€¦I can take a wild guess.

If the ball is elastic, then it will expand when going to a higher elevation (lower atmospheric pressure). The gauge pressure may not change much.

If the ball is inelastic, then the absolute pressure in the ball will stay the same, but atmospheric pressure will drop with increased elevation, so the gauge should read higher. The specâ€™d pressure is a relative pressure reading. So when you bring a ball from your home in San Diego, to play in Denver, youâ€™ll need to let some air out. And reinflate it when you get back home.

But thatâ€™s only my wild guess, from watching thin plastic water bottles as I drive to lower elevations all the time.
